# Example crontab: wire periodic claude-event emissions into a host's cron.
#
# Each line below uses the `claude-event` CLI (from this repo, under
# tools/claude-event/) to drop a JSON event into ~/claude-events/. The
# `claude-event-watch` watcher picks events up automatically and surfaces a
# one-liner to the running Claude Code session. See ../../tools/claude-event/
# for the CLI's own README.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Installation
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
#
#   System cron (root-installed, all users): copy this file in place. It
#   MUST be a regular file owned by root — cron rejects symlinks with
#   "WRONG FILE OWNER" and refuses to load them.
#
#       sudo cp examples/cron/example.crontab /etc/cron.d/claude-events-example
#       sudo chown root:root /etc/cron.d/claude-events-example
#       sudo chmod 644       /etc/cron.d/claude-events-example
#
#   User cron (per-user, no root needed): paste the rows below into your
#   own crontab via `crontab -e`, and DROP the USER column from each row.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Prerequisites
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
#
#   1. The `claude-event` CLI must be on PATH. After cloning the repo, a
#      common pattern is to symlink it into a directory cron's PATH covers:
#
#          sudo ln -s /path/to/claude-watch/tools/claude-event/claude-event \
#                     /usr/local/bin/claude-event
#
#      Adjust the absolute paths in the rows below if you installed it
#      somewhere else.
#
#   2. The `claude-event-watch` watcher must be running for emissions to
#      reach Claude Code. See tools/watchers/claude-event-watch.
#
#   3. Replace every literal `USER` below with the username that should
#      execute the job (e.g. `alice`). System cron rows REQUIRE the USER
#      column between the schedule fields and the command; user-crontab
#      rows do NOT have it.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# PATH
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Cron's default PATH is minimal (/usr/bin:/bin). Set an explicit PATH so
# /usr/local/bin and ~/bin are reachable.
PATH=/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin:/home/USER/bin

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Pattern 1 — direct one-liner heartbeat
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Use when the cron line itself is the entire signal you want to emit.
# The tag is freeform; pick something descriptive and either route it in
# your own claude-event routing table or just watch it land via
# `claude-event-tail`.
0 * * * * USER /usr/local/bin/claude-event "hourly heartbeat" --tag generic-heartbeat --source cron

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Pattern 2 — script wrapper that checks then conditionally emits
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Use when the emission depends on some external state (disk space,
# service health, queue depth, etc.). The script does the check and
# only emits when there's something to surface. See
# examples/cron/disk-space-check.sh for a working example.
*/10 * * * * USER /home/USER/repos/claude-watch/examples/cron/disk-space-check.sh

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Pattern 3 — daily heartbeat with structured metadata
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# `--data KEY=VAL` is repeatable; each pair is recorded under the event's
# `data` field. Use it for state the consumer might want to pivot on
# (window, severity hints, source IDs, etc.).
0 9 * * * USER /usr/local/bin/claude-event "daily morning ping" --tag morning-ping --source cron --data window=morning --data timezone=local
